Verrecchia said he relied entirely on EDC staff to report on 38 Studios finances







Thursday
Sep 24, 2015 at 4:49 PM
Sep 24, 2015 at 4:49 PM






				By Kate Bramson Journal Staff Writer
			
PROVIDENCE, R.I. -- Alfred J. Verrecchia, who was vice chairman of the R.I. Economic Development Corporation and chairman of Hasbro toy company when the EDC board approved the 38 Studios loan deal in 2010, never reviewed any financial records from the company, he told First Southwest's lawyer, Gerald J. Petros.
Instead, Verrecchia said he relied entirely on EDC staff and three professional advisory firms the agency retained -- Wells Fargo, First Southwest and Strategy Analytics -- to analyze 38 Studios' fiscal situation.
"Did you ever ask to review yourself the financial plan prepared by 38 Studios?" Petros asked.
"No," Verrecchia replied.
Petros: "Why not?"
Verrecchia: "I was relying upon the staff of EDC. It would have taken me an awful lot of time and energy that I didn't have to go in and review their financial plan."
Further, Verrecchia's deposition reveals that he and one other EDC board member -- Stephen Lane, then CEO of medical-device company Ximedica -- were e-mailed by an EDC administrative assistant that Keith Stokes wanted them to know about a meeting on April 9, 2010 with then-Governor Carcieri, Curt Schilling, Mike Corso, Keith Stokes and J. Michael Saul. Asked why he he was invited to meet with Schilling by the Governor, Verrecchia said he could not recall why. He insisted he did not attend that meeting.
A later e-mail between Verrechia and Lane that was discussed during the deposition indicated Lane attended what was referred to as “the Curt Schilling ‘Pitch’” meeting.
“I was not at the ‘Pitch’ meeting,” Verrecchia said. “I don’t know what went on at the ‘Pitch’ meeting. He [Lane] was there. He’s asking me if I had been appraised of the ask, and I said I have not appraised, so I have no idea what went on at the Curt Schilling ‘Pitch’ meeting, which is his terminology, not mine.”
Verrechia said he recalled the EDC's Saul asking if he could speak to anyone at Hasbro about the video-game business. Verrecchia, who had stepped down as Hasbro CEO in 2008, noted that Hasbro licensed its “properties to video game developers to, you know, exploit our intellectual property in the video game market.”
An e-mail discussed during Verrecchia’s deposition from Saul to Corso and Stolzman on April 12, 2010, sought to schedule a meeting with Verrecchia, Lane, then-Hasbro CEO Brian Goldner, Stokes, Schilling and one to two 38 Studios board members.
By April 22, Saul was writing to Verrecchia about his agreeing to introduce EDC staff to Mark Blecher at Hasbro as part of the “38 Studios’ due diligence.” Verrecchia said Blecher worked for Hasbro and was responsible for video-game activities, primarily licensing agreements with video game distributors, licensed intellectual property.” It appeared from documents that the meeting between Saul and Blecher took place April 29, 2010, Verrecchia confirmed. A later e-mail about that meeting indicated another Hasbro employee attended – James Jones, whom Verrecchia said he did not know.
Verrecchia insisted he and Lane were not working with EDC staff on the 38 Studios transaction before the full board knew about the transaction.
From his work at Hasbro, the world's second-largest toy company with approximate revenue of $4.2 billion when he retired as CEO in 2008, Verrecchia said in his deposition that he was familiar with the video-game industry, knew that delays with game releases were common and says he spoke to the EDC board about the risks and insisted the loan should not close unless the EDC retained a third-party monitor that would evaluate 38 Studios with a goal of keeping the company on track to make the game. Verrecchia said he didn't learn that a third-party monitoring agreement never was reached until long after the fact.
Verrecchia noted on more than one occasion in his deposition that Stokes talked about then-Speaker Fox’s interest in the 38 Studios transaction: “All Keith Stokes said was that the Legislature had passed this job creation bill and that the $75 million was earmarked at that time for 38 Studios, and he indicated that the Speaker will be unhappy if we were to take that $75 million and give it to somebody else,” Verrecchia said.
In late 2008, Carcieri had selected Verrecchia to lead a review of the EDC. In 2009, Verrecchia authored a scathing report blasting Rhode Island's economic-development efforts and the state agency charged with creating and retaining jobs, calling the agency "fragmented, disjointed and without focus." 
In announcing those findings, Verrecchia compared the EDC to a "basket of frogs," and said the agency's director should be replaced with a "professional economic development executive" and board members should be "qualified and able to establish strategy, ensure accountability and drive performance."
By January 2010, Carcieri appointed a new board, with Verrecchia as vice chairman, after a national search for a new EDC director failed to produce results. A month earlier, Ioanna T. Morfessis, hired as that new chief, abruptly resigned, before she was set to take over. 
The state's lawyer Max Wistow represented Verrechia at the deposition but said there would be no fee – Wistow said he was not getting paid, “except on the contingency basis that everybody knows about.”













